segments.text: we were talking about previous planning directors and the different contributions they have made and in what ways they may have been unique in contributing to planning in austin the next planning director was mike mahoney and how would you characterize his contributions or his emphasis that impacted planning in austin well actually he was here i think a good bit longer than bill parker and i think that he actually saw the department grow from just
a few staff members to a fairly sizable staff.
A lot of the current mapping that was started under Mike Mahoney, he worked toward the first master plan that was adopted by the city.
The consultant, I believe, was hired during his
So I think that he was very influential in getting the first plan for Austin.
And the next planning director was?
Oral Osborn.
And his contributions to the park and to the city as regards to planning?
Well, one thing I would say that it continued.
The plan, I think, was adopted, I believe, after Hoyle took Mike's place, if I have my dates right.
And I think that Hoyle, too, worked with neighborhoods.
He was very concerned about neighborhood preservation.
He's very environmentally concerned.
He has always been interested in the protection of the water system, the lake area, and the hill country.
So all in all, all our, I think, planning directors have been really very dedicated in preserving Austin.
Can you give me an idea approximately when Mr. Mahoney and Mr. Osborne began working as director in the department?
Well, Mr. Mahoney was the director when I came to work in 1955.
He was also here in 54 when I worked part-time, when I worked one summer.
So I think that Mike might have been here, he either came in 52 or 53, I believe.
And I believe that he left, oh, more than likely,
close to the 60s, or late 50s, and then while Osborne became the director.
And he was director until Mr. Lilly came along, which was when?
I can't, well, I believe that Mr. Lilly has been director about eight years.
I'm not sure if it's 72 or in that ballpark.
And each planning director, of course, has a different type of emphasis, different fields of interest, and that impacts the fields of planning within Austin.
What would you say the role of outside consultants has been in planning in Austin?
Have they been valuable?
Yes, they have been.
Now, we had a consultant, of course, way back in 1928, and I cannot give you how much influence that consultant had.
However, there were some zoning categories that were developed as a result of his plan, and I think that that does affect the community.
The next consultants that I'm aware of would be the Farron Granger,
And, of course, the influence on the thoroughfare plan that was adopted by the Council at that time.
And then...
Approximately 61.
No, that was in the 50s, early 50s.
And the next one was specific planning and research, or the Harold Wise Group out of California.
They changed title while they were working for us.
And they were the ones who were the consultants for the plan that was adopted in 61.
The plan that was written by them was much more comprehensive than the one that was adopted.
And you would say that even to this day, outside consultants play a valuable role.
Oh, yes.
At this time, how are they utilized?
Well, at this time, we have a consultant from California who is working on the revision or the rewrite or new revision
or every way you might want to call it, zoning ordinance.

And so they are drawing, of course, from their expertise and experience throughout the country in regard to zoning, and I feel as though that it will be quite influential, or they will be quite influential on Austin if that ordinance is adopted.
Several types of factors influence planning in the community, and I'd like to go over some of these.
What type of political influences have impacted planning in Austin?
Well, that's, I think, one of the more difficult questions that we have.
We have the state capitol, of course, here.
We are affected, I think, because the state legislation takes place here.
And I don't think you can be completely immune from that.
So even though our local politics are separate, I think there's a certain influence, even from the state politics.
Locally, the political picture, I think, has changed in recent years.
It used to be where we had, I would say, a fairly stable old school political situation, where we had a lot of the Alstonites who were from old families who carried
a lot of influence on the entire political picture.
I don't know whether you recall Tom Miller, but he was one of our most influential mayors, a very strong mayor, a very dedicated person wanting Austin to be as good as possible.
He, I think, had some far-reaching
theories, just like he was the one who influenced the acquisition of City Park way out in the lake when he had a lot of opposition, but he was a strong man and he accomplished it.
That was when approximately?
Oh, goodness.
I don't know the year, but again, it was quite a number of years ago.
So I feel as though that we've had some very strong political figures.
The mayor who was
in office at the time that the 61 plan was adopted.
The 61 plan had been prepared and completed in 58, and it had been more or less dormant because we had a good bit of opposition to it.
But at that time, Lester Palmer was our mayor, and he felt very strongly about it, and he knew that he was not going to run for office again, and he decided that he would
He wanted, I think, to see the plan adopted.
And he made a special effort in working on it.
And even though it was not as comprehensive as the original one had been written, it was modified.
And he helped with the revision of it so that it was acceptable
to the political community, and we got it adopted.
In cities that utilize a city manager, occasionally the city manager will have a good deal of influence on planning.
Has this been the case in Austin?
Yes.
Actually, when I came, I think
Walter C. Holm, I believe, was city manager.
And then Mr. W.T.
Williams came in, and he worked very closely with us.
He was a former city attorney.
He, I think, had been involved in writing of a number of the ordinances, like involved in subdivision and zoning.
actually kept his finger on the pulse of every part of the community in Austin.
In other words, he wanted to know what was going on in every area.
And he was the type of person who never took a vacation.
I mean, his work, I think he loved his work.
And I think that for that reason, he wanted to know every angle of it.
I know that at the time that we were working on
Interstate 35.
I was one of the new young planners at that time and this was when Tom Miller was in office and they wanted a model of what interstate was going to look like.
And here I was fairly fresh out of the university and I got the job to build it and
Tom Miller always stayed interested in it.
And Mr. Williams, he would, I'd be working late at night, Mr. Williams would come up and, I mean, he had first-hand interest in everything that was going on.
I mean, he wanted progress for the community, but again, he kept posted on everything that was happening.
And let's say in the present, the present city manager is...
Dan Davidson.
And what kind of influence has he had on planning and the planning department in Austin?
Well, I think that he, too, is very planning-oriented.
In fact, I think some of his background includes planning.

And I think that he, of course, wants the very best for Austin, and I think he recognizes that one of the ways of accomplishing the best for Austin is to have a good, comprehensive plan that can be followed.
Would you say that religious factors have been a significant influence on planning in Austin?
Maybe to a degree.
We have several religious schools here.
We have St. Edward's.

all Concordia and the Presbyterian seminary and of course they take out blocks of land that affect us physically the tax base and the tax base so I think it has as far as you know the religious community otherwise I don't think that it has some in other words we do not have
We're not made up of just basically one religion that would more or less establish the rules for the city.
I think that we have enough variation here so that I don't think that it's been a major influencing factor.
How have different ethnic groups been an influence on planning throughout the history of Austin?
I'm not sure whether they were involved a great deal.
I don't think that they were involved.
They have become involved in recent years.
In fact, we have quite a number of groups who are very vocal in regard to the planning for Austin.
There is a tendency for some of them to want to do all of their own planning.
regardless of whether they own the property or not.
If they live in the area, they want the full control of it.
And I think that this is...
I have found that the minority groups are... How can I put it?
A small section of them are very, very vocal and...
do not want to compromise.
I think that's about the only way I can put it at this time.
I found that in other areas there's more of a compromise and a let's work out the problem.
We've had a few instances recently where the group, this is what we want, we won't take anything else.
And so I think that there can be some instances where it can affect the community.
Do you see that in the planning department dealing with minority groups through whether it be independent or
representing neighborhood action-type groups, that they have their own neighborhood concerns, typically, or they have a comprehensive viewpoint and a large-scale view of the city as an area?
They do not take a large-scale view, but very few neighborhoods do this.
I mean, I think that that's across the board.
Most of them, I think, take a very narrow view.
One of the things that I think, and I don't think this is just in the ethnic groups, I don't think it deals only with that.
I think that any neighborhood tends to focus in on their problems and how they are affected.
Now, one of the things that I have noticed over and over again, and that is that if the planning department
or an outside agency suggests something for the community, they're immediately suspicious.
They feel as though that we're trying to do something to them, not for them.
And we had a case a number of years ago, and I think this will illustrate it, where we were trying to roll back a large area of East Austin
from industrial to residential, because the area was developed residentially with small lots, and we did not want industries to come in and disrupt the neighborhood.
We proposed it, and you just wouldn't believe the opposition that we got.
They felt as though we were trying to take something away from them.
Last year, we had a group come in.
And it was more or less initiated by themselves for a rollback.
The neighborhood leaders were supposed to have met with everybody to try to inform them.
But even at that, we had a few people at the hearings who felt as though somebody was trying to pull something.
They're immediately suspicious, even though we have, say,
the same concerns that they have, the protection of the neighborhood.
How have geographic factors influenced planning in Austin, centralized location, etc.?
One thing, we are on the edge of the hill country.
So as you know, part of our city is, part of our very best development is in the hill country.
what used to be considered west of Austin.
It's not west of Austin anymore.
It's part of Austin.
And then, of course, we have the farmlands east of Austin and south.
So, of course, you might be talking about the geographic in the relationship that we're on Interstate 35.
where between, say, Houston and Waco, I mean, San Antonio and Waco, if that's the sort of thing that you're talking about, I think that being close to these other large cities is an advantage.
We're far enough away still.
A lot of people consider Austin a small town, which it isn't anymore, but it still has a lot of...
or unique characteristics that the big cities of Houston and Dallas don't have.

And so I think that being still close to these centers, because it doesn't take long to get to Dallas or Houston, you can fly there very, very quickly if you need to, but still you can have a better place to live by being in Austin.
The other thing, when we're talking about topography, geography, whatever way you want to get into that, we have the variety that Houston and Dallas don't have.
San Antonio has some of it, but again, I still think that Austin has the very best, because it has a little of everything.
How has this played a role in, let's say, choosing Austin for the capital site originally?
Well, I think that that is one reason it was chosen, is because it was on the edge of the various areas.
It's fairly centrally located.
Really, Austin is unique, and I think our forefathers saw this.
How about waterways?
Of course, the Colorado River had...
I think waterways have a major influence on the settlement of any community, and I think the Colorado River is our lifeline.
Sociological factors such as population, education of the populace here...
income levels and that affected planning in Austin?

Well, one thing, because of the university being here, because of San Marcos and Georgetown being close by, they're smaller universities, I think that our educational, the availability of varying types of educational levels, again, I've
have not looked at the figures, but I would dare say that the educational level of Austinites tends to be a little higher in most communities just because it's readily available.
And we have also some of the local religious schools here.
So we do have an influx of some people who are going to the seminaries and so on.
How has this influenced planning?
Has it been an influence?
I think it has been an influence.

I think that people in Austin, a lot of the people who are interested in the betterment of the community, the fact that they have been exposed to it as they got their training at the universities, as they participated in activities, they became more knowledgeable.
And I think that they have a greater interest as a result in Austin being the best possible place.
So you feel possibly that this has had an impact in citizen group participation and organization.
Oh yes, very definitely.
Directly as a result of these factors.
Economic influences, we've spoken earlier, have had an impact on planning.
On the whole, how would you characterize the importance of economic factors here in planning?
I think that the fact that we have been fairly stable up until just a couple years ago, Austin had the reputation of never losing a bond election.
And suddenly we've lost a few.
What was the first, for example?
Oh, goodness.
It might have been two or three years ago.
Not very long ago.
And I think that before that, Austin was more of a close-knit community.
They did not have the outside influx at that time as much, and they wanted the best for the community, and they were willing to pay for it.
Now we've ended up with...

more people from outside and unfortunately a lot of them feel now that i'm here i want to close the door i don't want any more people to come it's nice as it is i don't want to mess it up because we have kept our standards high that's the reason it is as desirable as it is problem that we're going to have is that as the city grows there's more demand for services
Your efficiency, the larger you get, the more your efficiency drops off.
So per capita, I'm sure that it's going to cost us more to operate the city and to provide the services that people want, partly because we are larger in the physical sense.
We have to extend our services further and further out.
and partly because the people are coming in with suburban sprawl that we would like to discourage but this is what the people want.

They do not want concentrations and so the services continue to go up because they need to be extended further and further and the very people who are speaking against it are the ones who are moving into these areas and I don't know how we can
settle that issue because in itself it is a contradiction.
But I think that all we can do is to try to work with it, but it does affect the economic capability of continuing to provide the services that people want without increasing taxes.
I see a number of conflicts on the economic front.
You mentioned earlier that over 50% of the land area in Austin cannot be taxed by the city of Austin.
You mentioned the desirability because of its location next to the hill country, recreational opportunities, influx of population
would naturally be occurring here because industries are attracted to make up for that lack of tax base.
On the other hand, growth management has to be considered and has been considered in the Austin Tomorrow Plan.
What are some of the other ways historically that Austin has tried to deal with this conflict through planning?
In regard to establishing areas that
We've tried to encourage the higher intensity uses to happen on the major arterioles.
We have hoped that by encouraging the high intensity uses that might be traffic generators
so that maybe a mass transit system can function.
And that goes back into our economics, because right now, without government assistance, we would be running at a tremendous deficit, I'm sure.
It's difficult to maintain the service and still keep the prices down.
But all of it goes back into the fact that Austinites moved here.
because we have a lot of amenities.
The amenities cost money.
And there is always kind of a break point when people say that I can't afford this anymore.
But you get young families in, and many times they do not see this correlation.
And when it comes right down to it, there are very few people who have
the interest of the full community at heart unless it affects them some way or benefits them in some way.
And you'll find that, for instance, people who have a number of children in schools, they'll tend to vote for the bond program for improvement in any of the school system.
You will find that because of Austin now, we're ending up with a lot of retired people
who are empty nesters.
They are on fixed income.
They don't use the streets very much.
They don't get out there during peak hours anymore.
They're set.
They're not trying to move into another home, out into another area or anything like that.
Any growth to them is...
infringement upon their right to privacy.
That's right.
And so they, I think most of them, will tend to vote against any improvements, either to the school system, street system, or for any gross
even if it might be in what we call our selected growth corridor, because they have really no interest in it.
All it will do is to possibly raise their taxes, and they can't afford it.
So because of, say, the retirement situation, and, for instance, universities,
University has a tremendous effect on this, too, because they can vote.
And most of those people, of course, a lot of them end up staying here.
I did.
And I know of a lot of my friends who did, because Austin is nice.
But while they're at the university, they look at the things in a very theoretical sense.
They don't realize the impact on the entire community,
what, say, a bond election, how it might affect it if it's turned down versus whether it's passed.
So we can end up with a lot of problems on the economic situation because of our makeup of university, a lot of retired people, military, the whole
That was the next factor I was going to ask you about, that of the military influence on planning in Austin.

Well, one thing that I had not covered earlier, which I should have, and that is the Bergstrom Air Force Base has affected a lot of our planning, physical planning, because of the sound and the noise factors around Bergstrom Air Force Base.
We're recommending a lot of industrial development in the area where we have noise problems.
And so that has affected our land use situation because some of that area is not desirable for residential because of noise or safety.
I'm not sure I asked you earlier, but when did Bergstrom get rid of it?
I can't tell you.
I can't tell you offhand.
Because I would say that more than likely in the late...
thirties or early forties.
And physical planning was to the greatest extent impacted by them?
Yes.
Now I can get that information for you if you'd like to have that.
We'll get that at a later time then.
Finally then, what would you, very briefly, could you describe the current status of planning in Austin?
Well I think that we are
Of course, I guess you'd consider that we'd be blowing our own horn.
I think that Austin is about as advanced in regard to planning as any community can be.
We have, I think, one of the most forward-looking planning directors we've ever had.
We consider the public input from every group possible.
We encourage public input.
development community, investment community, to work within the framework of the community.
Because they are going to be part of the community.
They will either provide jobs for the community or provide a service to the community.
And their income will be based on the community's support.
We are one big family.
And I think that we try to encourage the people to work together.
Because a business locating in an area, they are not isolated from the residential.
Their service area is the residential community.
And so they should complement, they should provide a service, and that residential community should feel good about that commercial area being there.
The same way about our transit system, same way about our thoroughfare system.
It is there.
